In this article, President Biden discusses cancer developments and the impact on soldiers returning home with brain cancers due to exposure to toxins in the air, such as burn pits and IEDs. He emphasizes the need for research and government focus on this issue, drawing a parallel to the challenges faced with Agent Orange exposure. The President expresses hope in potential immunotherapy initiatives, specifically mentioning the use of adenovirus injections into the brain. He also discusses the benefits of FLASH therapy, proton therapy, and immunotherapy in cancer treatment. President Biden regrets having to give up the Biden Cancer Initiative due to lack of funding and mentions the involvement of Nobel laureates in the initiative. The article concludes with a brief mention of the President's hope for political capital to make changes on gun measures.